    "narrative": "For April 17, LawDog\u2019s offensive profile is anchored by the high-efficiency matchup for **Will Smith** (74.95), who benefits from a prime hitting environment and a favorable draw against Sugano. **Lawrence Butler** (73.47) stands out as our most aggressive play; despite the lower batting order spot, his dynamic platoon edge and park factors against Martin make him an elite starting option today. We are also projecting significant contributions from our middle-of-the-order stalwarts, with **Matt Chapman** (68.06) and **Luis Arraez** (65.76) providing high-floor production against the vulnerable arm of Littell. While **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (64.81) faces a tougher matchup against Bassitt, his sustained base talent ensures he remains a must-start staple in the utility slot to maximize our pursuit of 5x5 counting stats.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Drew Gilbert** (49.83), who remains the closest candidate to cracking the active roster. While **Gilbert** projects well against Littell, he was ultimately nudged out by the combined platoon and order advantages possessed by **Jung Hoo Lee** (61.25) and **Wenceel Perez** (54.03). We are monitoring the risk profile of **Cal Raleigh** (46.92) closely; facing an elite arm like deGrom severely constrains his daily efficiency score, and while he is currently active, he represents a \"marginal\" start that we are keeping on a short leash to preserve our game caps. Similarly, **Taylor Ward** (53.92) is active, but his score is suppressed by a negative platoon shift against Bibee. We have finalized this lineup to prioritize plate appearances against bottom-tier expected ERAs while holding the bench depth of **Brendan Donovan**, **Jonathan Aranda**, and **Jeremiah Jackson** in reserve should injury or late-scratches necessitate a shift.",
